description.value: Limestone head of a man with a tonsure: the man has a distinctive hairstyle: he is bald on top, with wavy locks at the sides and back, flaring out to partially cover his ear and the nape of his neck. This head, extensively bald but with well-groomed hair, is so different from conventional Egyptian representations of baldness that some have suggested it is a foreign style. Despite the fragmentary condition of the head, two small bits of evidence suggest that its original form was that of a block statue. In the first place, the damage to the chin suggests that something was attached across the bottom; since it was not a beard, the likeliest possibility is that it was his cupped hand. Secondly, we can see from the angle of the neck that the head was slightly raised. This rather uncommon detail is found occasionally on most types of Egyptian statues, but it appears with greatest frequency on block statues. There can be no doubt that this statue was of extraordinarily high quality. The form of the eyes and the lovely, generous mouth suggest a date in the late Eighteenth Dynasty.

description.value:
Fragmentary limestone head of a male figure, the right side of the face now lost.

He has a tonsure hairstyle of wavy curls around the side of the head and partly covering his left ear, while the top of the head is bald. His brow is deep set. The inner corner of his left eye is intact, while his right eye has been heavily damaged with a number of abrasions to the pupil area and around the edges. The remaining outline of his nose suggests it was broad in shape, and his mouth is wide with thick, fleshy lips. His lips are pursed together and sharply incised around the edge, while the outer corners of his mouth are relaxed. His chin appears to be raised, suggesting an upwards gaze.

There are numerous chips and thin scratches to the surface which obscures details of the facial features. A large portion of the top of the head is missing.

description.value: Egyptian terracotta figure head of comic actor wearing mask. A head of an actor, broken from a figure: with short curly hair, in a roll at the front and with a peak over the forehead, and indicated by gouges part way over the rear of the head. Heavy brows and jowls, high cheekbones and an open mouth; the bottom edge of the mask is indicated, the lower part of the head showing below. The figure would seem to represent an Old Woman of the New Comedy.  The head is solid and the face may have been formed in a one-piece mould, with heavy subsequent hand-modelling, but is more likely to have been completely handmade. Overall white dressing with traces of orange-pink paint on the flesh. Red-brown Nile silt with frequent fine gold mica and quartz inclusions.

A head of an actor, broken from a figure: with short curly hair, in a roll at the front and with a peak over the forehead, and indicated by gouges part way over the rear of the head. Heavy brows and jowls, high cheekbones and an open mouth; the bottom edge of the mask is indicated, the lower part of the head showing below. The figure would seem to represent an Old Woman of the New Comedy.  The head is solid and the face may have been formed in a one-piece mould, with heavy subsequent hand-modelling, but is more likely to have been completely handmade. Overall white dressing with traces of orange-pink paint on the flesh. Red-brown Nile silt with frequent fine gold mica and quartz inclusions.

description.value: Corinthian terracotta doll of a female dancer. Head and body section only of a mould-made doll. Dancer wears polos and a short chiton, peculiar to dancers and young girls of that period. The missing arms may have carried castanets or tambourines as they do with other examples. Would have had separately articulated limbs, lost in antiquity. String hole for attaching arms runs between shoulders. Broken at the abdomen where legs would have been attached in a similar way. A hole in the top of the head has an uncertain function. Pressed into a one-piece mould with a plain flat, roughly finished back.  Traces of black paint on hair. Red-beige clay with beige core sandwiched between dark pink-red outer margins and beige surfaces. Common fine angular grey, white and red inclusions as well as vesicles.

description.value: Egyptian terracotta figure of Aphrodite. Head inclined to the left wearing a Stephane (diadem), detached from the large figure of the goddess Aphrodite. Very well modelled, the hair parted in the centre and richly waved, drawn back to a bun, with some of the long tresses brought to the top of the head and knotted there. In front of these tresses is a plain diadem. The neck is angled, and radiating grooves were cut across its lower edges to key it to the separately made body to which it was attached. The head is hollow, and mould-made, with added and manipulated hair.  Traces of an overall white dressing covered by red paint on the back of the neck and black on the hair. Orange-brown Nile silt with a grey core, frequent, fine gold mica and common white and black inclusions.

description.value: Egyptian terracotta seated figure of Harpokrates. He is naked and has a large phallus (chipped) reaching to his knees. At his left side his lowered left hand is clenched into a fist; the right arm is raised with the palm out-turned. The throne is fairly featureless, with a cushion and a grooved leg defined. An extension to the throne at the figure’s right indicates that another feature was placed on that side. The back is undecorated, with a circular vent. Hollow, from two-piece mould. Orange-brown Nile silt with abundant fine gold mica, quartz and white grits.

description.value:
Black granite head from a fragmentary statue of a royal or divine female figure, the body and base now missing.

The figure wears a striated wig which is set low on the forehead and tucked behind the ears. The right side of the wig is broken off just below the ear while the left side is broken off at the neck area, though the wig likely extended to the chest. Along the centre of the wig above the forehead is the coiled body and hooded frame of the uraeus cobra, with its head now lost. The face is fleshy with narrow eyes and ong cosmetic lines extending to the temples. The mouth is wide and sharply incised along the bottom lip, with the outer corners visibly turned upwards to form a clear smile.

In addition to the breaks at the neck and wig, there are large cracks visible across the centre of the head with the left side damage extending across the face. description.value:
Worn limestone striding figure of a Ptolemaic king, possibly Ptolemy II, on a slim rectangular base.

The king wears a double-crown and nemes headcloth, both with visible traces of a darker paint across the surface. Striped bands across the lappets of the nemes headcloth are faded but still visible. A raised section of the stone at the forehead likely depicted a uraeus cobra, which has deteriorated. The facial features of the king are also now obscured, but the false beard is still intact. His upper body is bare, and he wears a shendyt kilt with a thick belt. The incised details of the clothing are now lost. Both arms are held by his sides and unidentified objects are held in both hands, possibly a piece of folded cloth. The body and legs are particularly broad in size, and the left leg strides forward ahead of the right. On the reverse is a broad back-pillar with a triangular top that reaches to the tip of the double-crown. The back-pillar appears to be uninscribed.

Worn limestone striding figure of a Ptolemaic king, possibly Ptolemy II, on a slim rectangular base.

The king wears a double-crown and nemes headcloth, both with visible traces of a darker paint across the surface. Striped bands across the lappets of the nemes headcloth are faded but still visible. A raised section of the stone at the forehead likely depicted a uraeus cobra, which has deteriorated. The facial features of the king are also now obscured, but the false beard is still intact. His upper body is bare, and he wears a shendyt kilt with a thick belt. The incised details of the clothing are now lost. Both arms are held by his sides and unidentified objects are held in both hands, possibly a piece of folded cloth. The body and legs are particularly broad in size, and the left leg strides forward ahead of the right. On the reverse is a broad back-pillar with a triangular top that reaches to the tip of the double-crown. The back-pillar appears to be uninscribed.

description.value:
Fragmentary limestone scribal figure of Iahmose, the head and upper body now lost.

Iahmose is seated in a cross-legged position and wears a short kilt reaching to his knees. There is an indication of a thick belt around his waist. The right forearm and outline of the now lost left forearm are placed flat on the thighs. Across the clothing in between his hands are five horizontal lines of hieroglyphic text, oriented towards Iahmose. The name of the god in the initial line of the text has been deliberately damaged. On the reverse a fragment of both arms also survive, and there is a suggestion of a narrowing at the waist.

In addition to the loss of the upper body and damage to the arms, there is a large chip to the reverse of the body and edge of the base, as well as to the front of the object at the edge of the kilt. The object has been attached to a tall tilted modern base.

description.value: A hollow terracotta camel, modelled in the round and standing on a low plain plinth. Details of the head-harness are indicated in relief, as are three girth straps, although the load, a domed bundle, is shown in paint. The right hind foot and part of the plinth are lost. Two-piece mould; striations (probably post-moulding but pre-firing) show hair on the neck. Micaceous brown Nile silt, painted over much of the surface with a white dressing, except for the spaces between the legs, which are black, together with the top edges of the plinth. All the applied coloration is probably post-firing, but not certainly so. The harness, on the head and neck, the eyes, the edges of the load, its strapping and girths are all picked out in black. Other strappings of the load are painted pink and yellow. Pink is also employed on the mouth, in a stripe round the animal's throat, and in horizontal bands round its lower legs. Yellow paint is used on the plinth and between the two black harness-straps on the neck.

description.value:
Terracotta figure of a Gaulish mercenary in the Ptolemaic army.
A standing Gaul in a proudly aggressive pose: he is largely naked, but wears a long cloak. His hair is long and rises from his forehead to fall in tresses on each side of his face and extends to the nape of his neck at the rear; his phallus is outsize. His long-sword is slung from a waist-belt on his right side and he grips the hilt, which is forked and has a knobbed guard: it is uncertain whether it is scabbarded. He holds a large oval Gaulish shield to his left side; it has a bound edge and a vertical spine with a central elongated boss. The boss has a looped plate on each side; two diagonal grooves cross the face above and below the boss. The rear is plain except for the Gaul’s hair and an edge of his shield; there is a circular vent. The legs are lost below the ankles.
Hollow; two-piece mould. Micaceous brown Nile silt.

description.value: A hollow terracotta camel, modelled in the round and standing on a low plain plinth. Details of the head-harness are indicated in relief, as are three girth straps, although the load, a domed bundle, is shown in paint. The right hind foot and part of the plinth are lost. Two-piece mould; striations (probably post-moulding but pre-firing) show hair on the neck. Micaceous brown Nile silt, painted over much of the surface with a white dressing, except for the spaces between the legs, which are black, together with the top edges of the plinth. All the applied coloration is probably post-firing, but not certainly so. The harness, on the head and neck, the eyes, the edges of the load, its strapping and girths are all picked out in black. Other strappings of the load are painted pink and yellow. Pink is also employed on the mouth, in a stripe round the animal's throat, and in horizontal bands round its lower legs. Yellow paint is used on the plinth and between the two black harness-straps on the neck.
